05200nam a22008175i 9781684482153DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019036604  a97816844821537 a10.36019/97816844821532doi  a(DE-B1597)567779  a(OCoLC)1181839424  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA00aPR708.L52bG87 2020 4aPR708.L52bG87 2020eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a822.5091 aGustafson, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLothario's Corpse :bLibertine Drama and the Long-Running Restoration, 1700-1832 /cDaniel Gustafson. 1aLewisburg, PA : bBucknell University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (258 p.) :b2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransits: Literature, Thought & Culture 1650-185000tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: The Long-Running Restoration -- t1 Corpsing Lothario -- t2 Debating Dorimant -- t3 Stuarts without End -- t4 Libertines and Liberalism -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLothario's Corpse unearths a performance history, on and off the stage, of Restoration libertine drama in Britain's eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. While standard theater histories emphasize libertine drama's gradual disappearance from the nation's acting repertory following the dispersal of Stuart rule in 1688, Daniel Gustafson traces its persistent appeal for writers and performers wrestling with the powers of the emergent liberal subject and the tensions of that subject with sovereign absolutism. With its radical, absolutist characters and its scenarios of aristocratic license, Restoration libertine drama became a critical force with which to engage in debates about the liberty-loving British subject's relation to key forms of liberal power and about the troubling allure of lawless sovereign power that lingers at the heart of the liberal imagination. Weaving together readings of a set of literary texts, theater anecdotes, political writings, and performances, Gustafson illustrates how the corpse of the Restoration stage libertine is revived in the period's debates about liberty, sovereign desire, and the subject's relation to modern forms of social control. Ultimately, Lothario's Corpse suggests the "long-running" nature of Restoration theatrical culture, its revived and revised performances vital to what makes post-1688 Britain modern. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEnglish dramay18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramay19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLibertines in literature. 0aLibertinism in literature. 0aTheater and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aTheater and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020z978311069033040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781684482153zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781684482153423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781684482153.jpg  a978-3-11-069033-0  RUP eBook-Packag